{"id":"1904.09831","submitter":"Niko Tratnik Dr.","authors":"Niko Tratnik","title":"Computing weighted Szeged and PI indices from quotient graphs","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Int. J. Quantum Chem. 119 (2019) e26006","doi":"10.1002/qua.26006","report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The weighted Szeged index and the weighted vertex-PI index of a connected\ngraph $G$ are defined as $wSz(G) = \\sum_{e=uv \\in E(G)} (deg (u) + deg\n(v))n_u(e)n_v(e)$ and $wPI_v(G) = \\sum_{e=uv \\in E(G)} (deg(u) + deg(v))(\nn_u(e) + n_v(e))$, respectively, where $n_u(e)$ denotes the number of vertices\ncloser to $u$ than to $v$ and $n_v(e)$ denotes the number of vertices closer to\n$v$ than to $u$. Moreover, the weighted edge-Szeged index and the weighted PI\nindex are defined analogously. As the main result of this paper, we prove that\nif $G$ is a connected graph, then all these indices can be computed in terms of\nthe corresponding indices of weighted quotient graphs with respect to a\npartition of the edge set that is coarser than the $\\Theta^*$-partition. If $G$\nis a benzenoid system or a phenylene, then it is possible to choose a partition\nof the edge set in such a way that the quotient graphs are trees. As a\nconsequence, it is shown that for a benzenoid system the mentioned indices can\nbe computed in sub-linear time with respect to the number of vertices.\nMoreover, closed formulas for linear phenylenes are also deduced. However, our\nmain theorem is proved in a more general form and therefore, we present how it\ncan be used to compute some other topological indices.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 22 Apr 2019 12:45:14 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 2 Jun 2019 19:23:01 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-11-11"}
